# JSON â†’ XML Converter âœ…

**Project:** JSON to XML Converter  
**Author:** Vidhyabathi K

---

## Overview ğŸ’¡
A small, dependency-free Python utility that converts JSON documents into a compact XML representation using a deterministic mapping. The converter supports JSON objects and arrays as top-level values and safely escapes XML special characters.

---

## Features âœ¨
- Pure Python standard library only (no external dependencies)
- Deterministic mapping of JSON types to XML tags
- Proper XML escaping for text values
- Simple CLI: read JSON file â†’ write XML file

---

## Requirements ğŸ”§
- Python 3.6+ (uses f-strings)
- Cross-platform: Windows, macOS, Linux

---

## Build
No build is required. A convenience `build.sh` script is included for consistency; the converter uses only Python standard libraries.

---

## Quick start â€” Run the converter â–¶ï¸

Usage:

```bash
python converter.py <input.json> <output.xml>
```

Example:

```bash
python converter.py tests/sample1.json result.xml
```

Expected output on success:

```
Conversion completed successfully
```

Exit codes:
- `0` â€” success
- `1` â€” usage error (wrong args) or invalid top-level JSON (must be an object or an array)

View the output file:
- On Linux/macOS: `cat result.xml`
- On Windows (PowerShell/CMD): `type result.xml` or open in an editor

---

## JSON â†’ XML mapping (details) ğŸ”
- JSON object â†’ `<object>` (child objects use `name="<key>"`)
- JSON array â†’ `<array>` (child arrays use `name="<key>"`)
- JSON string â†’ `<string>`
- JSON number â†’ `<number>` (int or float)
- JSON boolean â†’ `<boolean>` with `true`/`false` (lowercase)
- JSON null â†’ `<null/>` (self-closing; can include `name` attribute)

Notes:
- Keys of object properties are added as a `name` attribute on the child's element.
- Array elements are positional and do not have `name` attributes.
- All text content is escaped with `xml.sax.saxutils.escape` to ensure valid XML.

---

## Examples ğŸ“
Given `tests/sample1.json`:

```json
{
  "organization": {"name":"Securin","type":"Inc","building_number":4},
  "security_related": true,
  "array_example0": ["red","green"]
}
```

The XML output begins as:

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<object>
  <object name="organization">
    <string name="name">Securin</string>
    <string name="type">Inc</string>
    <number name="building_number">4</number>
  </object>
  <boolean name="security_related">true</boolean>
  <array name="array_example0"><string>red</string><string>green</string></array>
</object>
```

> Note: Output is compacted by default; you can pretty-print with external tools if you need human-readable indentation.

---

## Implementation notes & limitations âš ï¸
- The top-level JSON must be an object or an array; other types will cause the program to exit with an error.
- Unsupported Python types (custom objects) will raise `TypeError`.
- The converter loads the entire JSON into memory (not streaming) â€” for very large files, consider a streaming parser.
- No `--pretty` CLI flag is available in this version.

